Your Honours Project (also sometimes called a Dissertation or Final Year Project in other Universities) is a substantial piece of independent research and writing that you undertake in your final year of your undergraduate degree.

Think of it as the academic equivalent of a marathon or a master craftsman's final piece. It's not just another essay or exam; it's a long-term project that demonstrates everything you have learned throughout your degree.

Here are its key characteristics:

Independent Work: While you will have an academic supervisor to guide you, you are the driving force. You do the reading and background work, you design the methodology, you conduct the research, and you write it up.
Substantial: It's a major undertaking. The final word count is a minimum of 15,000 words (though this varies by subject and university), you will work on it throughout your final year.
Structured: It follows a formal academic structure: Introduction, Literature Review, Methodology, Results/Findings, Discussion, and Conclusion.
The Honours project is critically important for several reasons:
1. It's the Culmination of Your Degree
Your entire degree builds towards this point. It’s your chance to prove you can synthesise the knowledge, critical thinking skills, and research methods you've developed over three or four years and apply them to a single, deep question that fascinates you.

2. It Demonstrates Mastery and Independence
Universities want to award degrees to students who are not just passive learners but active scholars. The dissertation is the primary evidence that you can work independently, manage a large project, and contribute to your field of study, even in a small way. This is what separates an Honours degree from an ordinary degree.

3. It Heavily Influences Your Final Degree Classification
The dissertation is a triple module. This means it has a huge weighting on your overall final year grade. A strong dissertation can significantly boost your final degree classification (e.g., pushing a high 2:1 up to a First-Class degree), while a weak one can pull it down. Failing your honours project normally means that you can not be awarded an honours degree.

4. It Provides invaluable Skills for Your Future
This is arguably one of the most valuable aspects. The process teaches you skills that are highly sought after by employers and essential for further study:

Project Management: You learn to plan a long-term project, set deadlines, and manage your time effectively over many months.
Problem-Solving: You will inevitably hit obstacles and have to find creative ways around them.
Advanced Research & Analysis: You go far beyond a simple internet search, learning to find, evaluate, and synthesise complex information from academic sources.
Written Communication: You learn to construct a complex, persuasive argument at length and to a professional standard.
Resilience and Self-Discipline: It's a marathon, not a sprint. It requires consistent effort and the ability to motivate yourself.
5. It is Essential for Postgraduate Study
If you have any ambition to do a Master's degree or a PhD (a doctorate), your dissertation is crucial.

Master's Applications: It serves as a writing sample that proves you have the research capabilities to succeed at a higher level.
PhD Applications: Your dissertation topic can often form the foundation of a PhD research proposal. It shows you can identify a research gap and design a project to address it.
In Conclusion
The Honours project is your opportunity to become the expert on a topic you are passionate about. It's the most significant and rewarding piece of work you will do as an undergraduate. It’s challenging, but successfully completing it is incredibly satisfying and is a powerful testament to your abilities, setting you up for success whether you head into the world of work or continue in academia.

Definition of Honours Project

To stay within UK trusted research legislation an honours project is not an original, publishable artefact of research.

An honours project can be any project that is based upon published results. This can include published research papers.

For example, it could be:

Comparing two or more results published in research papers;
Using a published result in a new domain or applying it to a new problem;
Creating an artefact (such as an app) from a published result;
Looking at new ways of working, such as how AI can be used in industry, using a known system;
Looking at educational challenges a student might have faced in their degree and providing an artefact to help.
The University of Dundee has a Trusted Research Policy (“Policy”) and all honours projects must abide by the Policy’s terms and conditions. This policy is available at: https://www.dundee.ac.uk/research-governance-and-policy/trusted-research

Student Role


Ultimately, the project is the student's responsibility: the student is responsible for arranging and attending meetings, planning and doing the work and producing deliverables on schedule. The student is strongly recommended to arrange regular project meetings with the advisor, preferably weekly. It is the student's responsibility to liaise regularly with the advisor and to keep minutes of project meetings (to be included as an appendix in the final report). Students should please remember that most advisors are busy people like you: prepare for meetings and arrive on time. If you are going to miss a meeting, then it is good policy (and polite) to let your advisor know and reschedule the meeting as soon as possible.

The student is expected to devote an average of 18 hours per week to the project during the project weeks. This time does not all need to be spent at a computer. Valuable progress can be made by reading, thinking, planning and designing. It is up to the student to schedule the working week to cover the demands of the project and other modules: time management is a useful skill to develop in itself. If they put the effort in, they should find, like most students in the past, that their individual project is a very rewarding and worthwhile experience.

In summary students should:

Arrange a meeting with your advisor in the first week (which will be Week 3 of Semester 1). Agree the objectives of your project and try to ensure that these are as focused as possible.
Produce a project plan in conjunction with your advisor. It should identify deliverables to be submitted for interim assessment.
Arrange a schedule of meetings over the two semesters.
Attend meetings and keep the minutes along with other records of your activity, e.g. ideas, sketches, plans, tasks, reflections, to-do items, prototypes, etc. Some project advisors may suggest that you could use a Logbook for this (which may be hardcopy or electronic).
Attend and actively participate in timetabled workshops.
Submit all deliverables on time.
Re-plan if necessary, but always with the agreement of the advisor.
Put in an average of at least 17.5 hours per week of effort.